"Water use represents the meeting point between technology and health. A water-supply system's performance is not judged solely by its capacity to provide water, but by the extent to which it is used by the beneficiaries and, consequently, by its impact on a population's health status. 40 ''In water supply and sanitation programmes, planners have come to realize that community participation, among other things, is essential for projects to be successful. This represents a vast change from former projects in which the community was seen as a passive recipient of facilities planned and provided by the central government.'' Anne Whyte, Guidelines for Planning Community Participation Activities in Water Supply and Sanitation Projects (Geneva: WHO, 1986), p."